nodes.title: System Prompt -- Common description technique
widgets_values:
A structured approach helps with the result. The following categories are to be used:
1. Subject: Clearly define the central person, object, or theme.
2. Description and action: Use vivid adjectives and action verbs to elaborate on the subject and its activity. This adds depth and complexity.
3. Environment and setting: Describe the background and setting to provide context for the scene.
4. Style and medium: Indicate the desired artistic style, medium, or movement, such as "photo," "oil painting," "3D rendering," "impressionist," "cyberpunk," or by referencing an artist like "in the style of Van Gogh".
5. Lighting and atmosphere: Define the mood and lighting, using terms like "somber," "vibrant," "introspective," or descriptions such as "warm sunlight filtering through the trees". 
6. Technical details (optional): Include technical details like camera settings for more control, especially for photorealistic results, such as "Highly detailed, with realistic textures and global illumination". 

For each category, provide enough details to clearly define the category and its expected characteristics: "a cat" might be "an orange cat posing in the sun".

A suggested formula for prompts is: 
[Subject and Description], [Action and Interaction], [Environment and Setting], [Mood and Atmosphere], [Style and Technical Details]. 

Imperative: Your entire response must be only the final, converted prompt. Do not include any conversational text, labels, or explanations.

nodes.title: System Prompt
widgets_values:
You are an image generation tag-based to narrative conversion specialist: You will be given an "INPUT" of tag-based prompt that uses comma separation and numerical weights (e.g., (word:1.2)). Your task is to analyze these tags and their weights to identify the core subject, action, environment, and style, then synthesize them into a descriptive narrative, respecting the importance of weighted words. 
The final narrative must describes the expected iamge with natural language to produce a result following the expectations of the original prompt. 
The final narrative must consist of 4 to 10 sentences. Each sentence must be under 60 words.

nodes.title: System Prompt
widgets_values:
You are a image generation prompt narrative specialist. 
You are given ideas or an input text for image concepts in a "DIRECTIONS" section. Those "DIRECTIONS" might include some instructions on what to generate; when instructions are given, follow them. Some instructions will ask you to choose from a list of concepts: use your knowledge to assess the best combination possible in those cases.
Describe the expected image using a natural language narrative to produce the best result possible for the concepts and directions given. 
Identify each defined category (subject, action, environment, style, ...) then synthesize a descriptive narrative. 
This narrative will consist of 4 to 10 sentences. Each sentence must be under 60 words.

nodes.title: READ ME FIRST
widgets_values:
# Thank you for testing this "Combined Workflow" ❤️

This workflow is a Work-In-Progress combination, testing and tweaking various elements from other workflows to generate an upscaled 16MP image as the final result while staying as close as possible to the original and saving with CivitAI metadata (for each stage of the image generation).

In the process, I made use of SubGraphs and attempted to create the closest thing possible to "functions" in ComfyUI (I am **always** learning, so please do not hesitate to share methods).
This is a learning workflow: there are no hidden or pinned nodes.
It is also a Work-In-Progress workflow ... updates will be released when I am happy with the result.

I experimented, selected features and extended other workflows/steps to get to this version. 
Many thanks to the work of CivitAI's AlexLai, DigitalPastel, MrSmith2025, J1B and a few Redditors for sharing their work.

There are many nodes involved in this workflow, and you might need to retrieve a few models (SAM, Ultralytics, ...).

There are also many steps and sub-steps involved in this entire process. Because of that I made use of multiple subgraphs and Groups to keep the workflow organized and hopefully easier to navigate. The "How to use it" section tells you a few things about it. The "What it does" section explains what the different stages do.

Groups exist as an organizational structure for the entire process and follow the Stage numbers.

**It "works for me," but it might not be the best way to do it. Feedback is welcome.**

## How to use it
⬅️ Those are the fast toggles to use this workflow
- 🔴 groups ("02", ➡️) specify the `KSampler` models: you can only generate one type of image at at time (LoRAs are model specific so things will break otherwise)
  - each type of model can have its specific variables set in the selected SubGraphs: Checkpoint, VAE, CLIP (or model embedded ones for SDXL/Pony/Illustrious), `batch_size`, `steps`, `cfg`, `sampler`, `scheduler`, `clip_skip`, `seed`, `negative prompt` and `denoise`. Some of those values are set in 01c (🟢⬇️)
  - the positive prompt is set in 01c (🟢⬇️) and the `positive conditioning` is used for the `KSampler`.
    - the positive prompt is a concatenation of the various prompts combinations generated in the prompting group (including Ollama if available/enabled).
  - Each 🔴 KSampler outputs all the components needed for the 🔵 groups to work independently (think of it as `functions` in programming languages, I did not want to copy/paste the Subgraphs for each model independently)
    - This makes use of `Any Switch (rgthree)` and the logic present in `Parameters Selection`.
    - This allows the workflow to have independent Ksampler Subgraphs and a common set of "Stages" (see 🔵 group)
- 🟢 groups ("01", ↙️) are where prompt generation is done. 
  - Ollama is an option for transforming Wildcards prompts into narratives (01a) or help generate better narratives for prompts (01b). In 01a you can have Ollama extend the wildcards provided or convert a SDXL entry into a narrative. 01b is here to refine the content of 01a or to generate narratives based on the input provided. Modify the group's prompt to match your expectation.
    - Ollama usage: set the `url` to match your local instance (`Reconnect` will allow you to test the connection and list the available models) and a `keep_alive` value of `0` will drop the model (and release VRAM) right after generation.
    - When using Ollama, use an instruction tuned model (the default in the workflow is `gpt-oss:20b`, I have seen `Qwen2.5-0.5B-Instruct-GGUF` recommended for low VRAM usage if needed [untested]).
  - Narrative prompts only works for recent models: do not use those for SDXL or Pony. Instead, use classic tags or wildcards (01c)
  - Narrative prompts are recommended recent models (including Illustrious)
    - The `System Prompt` used for 01a and 01b is available in each group and can be tweaked.
  - In 01c you will be able to set LoRAs, positive (including wildcard use) and negative prompts (`trigger_words` for the LoRAs can be selected in the LoRA manager node)
    - the final prompt (Main + Ollama + Trigger Words + LoRAs list) can be reviewed
- 🔵 (↘️) groups are where the image processing is performed . The original image generation was done in 🔴(➡️). 

## What it does (the 🔵 group ↘️)
  - Stage 1 ("03" group): Candidate Selection; the workflow will pause and allow us to select which images to go to later stages
    - this can be bypassed (use the `Bypass Candidate Selection` toggle ⬅️)
    - I usually set the `batch_size` to 2 or 4 to allow me to review candidates before sending those to later stage (modify this in the corresponding `batch_size` parameter (in 01c ⬇️) if you prefer not to do this.
    - in this stage, a first `Image Saver` (Subgraph, 03b) is used. It will store images in folder based on Today's date, and use a file naming convention of: `%time_S1_%basemodelname_%seed` (S1 for "Stage 1"). 
    - CivitAI metadata is stored in the image: `model`, `sampler`, `scheduler`, `steps`, `cfg`, `clip_skip`, `seed`, full `positive_prompt` and `negative_prompt` (including LoRAs, Embeddings...). `width` and `height` are calculated based on the generated image. The workflow should also be embedded in the resulting PNG file (although CivitAI still does not show me the `Nodes` button in the generated images).
      - later stages are named `S2`, `S3`, `S4`.
    - it is possible to bypass specific "Image Savers" steps using the toggles; for example, to only keep the final (S4) image
  - Stage 2 ("04"): Upscale (or not) to 3 or 4 MP using HiResFix (SubGraph)
    - MP value can be changed. Keep 4 as a maximum as the next step are detailers and image regeneration.
  - Stage 3 ("05"): Upscaled Image Regeneration (Resampler) + Faces, Eyes & Hands Detailer (SubGraph)
    - It is possible to use "Alternate Models" (SDXL, Pony, Illustrious) for this step to speed up the process and reduce the VRAM usage. If doing so, make sure to 1) use a model that match the style of the image 2) the prompt will be passed to the resampler and detailler steps, if you prompt was a narrative, use Illustrious. Both can be enabled in the "Reduce Stage 3 ..." Muter selection  (⬅️). Likely not needed with SDXL/Pony/Illustrious base models generation (02a).
    - Using `Ultimate SD Upscaler (No Upscale)` to regenerate the upscaled image with the **original model and LoRAs**. 
    - Faces, Eyes and Hands Detailers are then used on the resulting image (specific detailers can be bypassed ⬅️)
      - Models are available as parameters (SAM, Ultralytics) as well as other common detection parameters.
  - Stage 4 ("06"): Upscale from 12 to 16 MegaPixels using SeedVR2 and Color Matching against first upscale (SubGraph)
    - That result is sent to SeedVR2 to generate a final 16MP image
    - MP value can be changed (16MP works on 24GB VRAM, higher did not, adapt as needed)
    - SeedVR2 models can be selected. Note: SeedVR2 Color correction is set to `None` to try to stay as close as possible to the original image.
      - for art, use a `sharp` model.
    - a "Color Match" step is then performed to try to match the final image against the original image

The "comparer" image shows the result of the first upscale against the final upscale
